  "text": "The Kubernetes scheduler framework plugin extension points are defined in kubernetes/kubernetes. The core interface definitions for all nine extension points (PreFilter, Filter, PreScore, Score, Reserve, Permit, PreBind, Bind, and PostBind) are located in pkg/scheduler/framework/interface.go. These interfaces define the contracts that scheduler plugins must implement at each extension point:\n\n1. **PreFilterPlugin** (line 512): Called at the beginning of the scheduling cycle, allows plugins to reject pods early or filter nodes.\n\n2. **FilterPlugin** (line 540): Filters out nodes that cannot run a pod. This is the core filtering phase where nodes are eliminated.\n\n3. **PostFilterPlugin** (line 561): Called after filtering fails, typically used for preemption or other recovery mechanisms.\n\n4. **PreScorePlugin** (line 587): Informational extension point called after filtering, allows plugins to record state before scoring.\n\n5. **ScorePlugin** (line 607): Scores filtered nodes to determine the best node for pod placement.\n\n6. **ReservePlugin** (line 624): Called to reserve resources for a pod before binding. Includes an Unreserve method for rollback.\n\n7. **PreBindPlugin** (line 640): Called before pod binding, allows plugins to perform final validations or setup.\n\n8. **BindPlugin** (line 673): Responsible for actually binding the pod to a node.\n\n9. **PostBindPlugin** (line 649): Called after successful binding, typically used for cleanup or informational purposes.\n\nThe framework implementation that manages these plugins is in pkg/scheduler/framework/runtime/framework.go. The frameworkImpl struct (starting at line 52) stores slices of each plugin type and implements the Framework interface. The getExtensionPoints method (line 103) maps the plugin configuration to the framework's internal plugin slices.\n\nPlugin registration is handled through pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/registry.go, which contains the NewInTreeRegistry function that registers all built-in plugins with their corresponding extension points. Individual plugins like defaultbinder.DefaultBinder (pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/defaultbinder/default_binder.go) implement the specific plugin interfaces and are registered through factory functions that return framework.Plugin implementations.\n\nThe scheduling framework follows a clear execution pattern where plugins are invoked at their respective extension points during the pod scheduling cycle, allowing for modular and extensible scheduling logic."
}

